Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// In your MCP server project
public class WeatherTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public WeatherTool(HttpClient httpClient)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<string> GetForecastAsync(string city)
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync($"https://api.weather.com/{city}");
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
dotnet add package Moq           # optional, for other interfaces
```

**3. Use a fake `HttpMessageHandler` to mock HTTP calls**

```csharp
// Helpers/MockHttpHandler.cs
public class MockHttpHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    private readonly Func<HttpRequestMessage, HttpResponseMessage> _handler;

    public MockHttpHandler(Func<HttpRequestMessage, HttpResponseMessage> handler)
        => _handler = handler;

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
        => Task.FromResult(_handler(request));
}
```

**4. Write tests**

```csharp
public class WeatherToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_ReturnsExpectedJson()
    {
        // Arrange — fake API response
        var handler = new MockHttpHandler(req =>
        {
            Assert.Contains("seattle", req.RequestUri!.AbsoluteUri);
            return new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK)
            {
                Content = new StringContent("{\"temp\": 62}")
            };
        });

        var httpClient = new HttpClient(handler);
        var tool = new WeatherTool(httpClient);

        // Act
        var result = await tool.GetForecastAsync("seattle");

        // Assert
        Assert.Contains("62", result);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_HandlesApiError()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpHandler(_ =>
            new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.ServiceUnavailable));

        var tool = new WeatherTool(new HttpClient(handler));

        await Assert.ThrowsAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => tool.GetForecastAsync("seattle"));
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| Inject `HttpClient` | Lets you swap in a fake handler at test time |
| `MockHttpHandler` | Intercepts HTTP at the lowest level — no real network calls |
| One test per behavior | Happy path, error codes, timeouts, malformed responses |
| No `IHttpClientFactory` needed | Direct injection is simpler for tool classes |

For more complex scenarios (multiple endpoints, ordered interactions), consider [WireMock.Net](https://github.com/WireMock-Net/WireMock.Net) which spins up a local fake HTTP server.
